  <rdf:Description rdf:about="http://ontology.amt.org/im#ProductCategory">
    <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:nodeID="n48ae1acd9db2458da0e88a17011b43fab29"/>
    <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="http://purl.org/nemo/gufo#ExtrinsicMode"/>
    <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:nodeID="n48ae1acd9db2458da0e88a17011b43fab30"/>
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class"/>
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://purl.org/nemo/gufo#Kind"/>
    <rdfs:seeAlso rdf:resource="http://ontology.amt.org/meta#CatalogValueShape"/>
    <rdfs:seeAlso rdf:resource="http://ontology.amt.org/views/exhibitor#ExhibitorOfferingShape"/>
    <amtmeta:scopedBy rdf:resource="http://ontology.amt.org/views/exhibitor"/>
    <rdfs:comment>Kind ⊑ gufo:ExtrinsicMode. Instances are concrete offering-aspects: each ProductCategory inheres in one Company (its bearer, via gufo:inheresIn) and externally depends on one pc: topic (via gufo:externallyDependsOn). Anti-rigid — a Company's offerings shift over time without losing Company-identity. Despite the class name, an instance represents 'this Company's offering of this pc: topic', not the topic itself. Runtime topic value-space defined by exhibitor_view:ExhibitorOfferingShape plus amtmeta:CatalogValueShape.</rdfs:comment>
    <rdfs:label>Product Category</rdfs:label>
  </rdf:Description>
